2 Type of Activities

td <- as.data.frame(table(data$activity))
labels <- paste(td$Var1, td$Freq, sep = ', ')

pie(td$Freq, 
    labels = labels, 
    col = rainbow(length(td$Freq)),
    main = 'Human Activity Data Counts')

4 Outlier Detection and Removal

activities <- unique(data$activity)
columns <- colnames(data)
columns <- columns[2:length(columns)]

for (activity in activities) {
  index <- which(data$activity == activity)
  for (column in columns) {
    x <- data[index, column]
    lower_fence <- unname(quantile(x, 0.25) - 1.5 * IQR(x))
    upper_fence <- unname(quantile(x, 0.75) + 1.5 * IQR(x))

    lower_indices <- which(data$activity == activity & data[column]<lower_fence)
    upper_indices <- which(data$activity == activity & data[column]>upper_fence)
    data2[lower_indices, column] <- NA
    data2[upper_indices, column] <- NA
  }
}

6 Statistical Test 1: Analyisis of Variances (ANOVA)

6.1 Normality Assumption Test (Shapiro-Wilk) for All Attributes across The Activities

for (activity in activities) {
  index <- which(data2$activity == activity)
  for (column in columns) {
    print(paste('Normality Assumption Test of Column:', toupper(column), 'and Activity: ', toupper(activity)))
    #print(ad.test(data2[index, column])$p.value > 0.05)
    print(shapiro.test(x = data2[index, column]))
    cat('\n\n')
  }
}

6.3 Parametric Test: ANOVA

for (column in columns) {
  print(paste('One-way ANOVA on Column:', toupper(column)))
  a <- aov(data2[,column] ~ data2$activity)
  b <- summary(a)
  print(b)
  cat('\n')
  if (b[[1]]$`Pr(>F)`[1] < 0.05) {
    print(paste('The variable', toupper(column), 'is significantly different in at least one of the groups.'))
    cat('\n')
    print(paste('Post Hoc Analyses on the variables.'))
    c <- TukeyHSD(a)
    print(c)
    
    t_df <- as.data.frame(c$`data2$activity`)
    diff <- names(c[1]$`data2$activity`[,1])[t_df$`p adj` < 0.05]
    print(paste('The following pairwise groups are different for', toupper(column)))
    for (d in diff){
      print(d)
    }
    
  }
  cat('\n\n')
}

6.4 Non-Parametric Test: Kruskal-Wallis Test

library(FSA)
## ## FSA v0.8.22. See citation('FSA') if used in publication.
## ## Run fishR() for related website and fishR('IFAR') for related book.
## 
## Attaching package: 'FSA'
## The following object is masked from 'package:car':
## 
##     bootCase
for (column in columns) {
  print(paste('Kruskal Wallis on Column:', toupper(column)))
  a <- kruskal.test(data2[,column] ~ data2$activity)
  print(a)
  cat('\n')
  if (a$p.value < 0.05) {
    print(paste('The variable', toupper(column), 'is significantly different in at least one of the groups.'))
    cat('\n')
    print(paste('Post Hoc Analyses on the variables.'))
    c <- dunnTest(data2[,column] ~ data2$activity,method = 'bh')
    print(c)
    
    t_df <- c$res
    diff <- t_df$Comparison[t_df$P.adj < 0.05]
    print(paste('The following pairwise groups are different for', toupper(column)))
    for (d in diff){
      print(d)
    }
    
  }
  cat('\n\n')
}
